<preface id="overview">
	<title>Overview</title>
	<para>
		jSLA is a Java library that allows applications written in Java
		or for JVM
		to enforce access
		to critical Java resources at
		configuration-defined rate and quotas. At
		the moment access
		is
		constrained based on usernames, groups and roles of remote users
		(authorities). A typical usage
		scenario for this library is when the
		application is under heavy usage, in
		this case access being
		allowed for
		some remote users (seen as critical) while others are temporary
		denied.
	</para>
	<para>
		Usage examples:
	</para>
	<para>
		<itemizedlist>
			<listitem>
				<para>
					Java standard web applications (JSP, Struts, Spring MVC and so
					on).
				</para>
			</listitem>
			<listitem>
				<para>
					Java Web Services.
				</para>
			</listitem>
			<listitem>
				<para>
					Other types of Java resources, such as those exposed in
					JSON/XML format.
				</para>
			</listitem>
		</itemizedlist>
	</para>

